<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,356,1064]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,371,463,488]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">
Notes on 
<typeStatus box="[309,371,463,488]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">types</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. Séguy (
<number box="[471,532,463,488]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" value="1963.0">1963</number>
: 
<number box="[543,586,463,488]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" value="254.0">254</number>
) based his description of 
<taxonomicName box="[874,984,463,488]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limatus">
<emphasis box="[874,984,463,488]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">P. limatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on a single male 
<typeStatus box="[1181,1279,463,488]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">holotype</typeStatus>
from “Paita”, [in Guangdong] 
<collectingCountry box="[336,407,500,525]" name="China" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">China</collectingCountry>
. We were unable to examine the 
<typeStatus box="[777,825,501,525]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">type</typeStatus>
in MNHN but have at hand a male from 
<collectingCountry box="[1289,1389,500,525]" name="Thailand" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and female from 
<collectingCountry box="[302,369,535,560]" name="Nepal" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">Nepal</collectingCountry>
that fit the description perfectly and use them for the diagnosis. In his original description, Séguy indicated that the genitalia were small (“ 
<emphasis box="[686,970,572,597]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">Appareil copulateur petit</emphasis>
”). This small size is more indicative of a female, which have exposed sclerites that can be confused as a minute hypandrium. It could be that Séguy had a female and not a male specimen. The 
<collectingCountry box="[578,629,644,669]" name="Thailand" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">Thai</collectingCountry>
specimen is clearly a male and has very large and distinct genitalia that are well exposed as is typical for species of 
<taxonomicName box="[643,767,679,704]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[643,767,679,704]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">Platypygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined in this study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="216" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,356,1064]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,428,716,741]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">Diagnostic features</emphasis>
. Face yellow; frons yellow on basal half, black on upper half; vertex black, yellow behind where joining occiput; occiput black with white hairs (
<figureCitation box="[782,867,751,776]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,249,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[184,1391,220,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[171,1412,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. Platypygus limatus, male specimen from Thailand: a — adult male (lateral view), b — adult male (dorsal view)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248559/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">
Fig. 
<number box="[837,867,752,776]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
a); mentum yellowish white; antennae completely black; mesonotum (
<figureCitation box="[389,478,788,813]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,249,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[184,1391,220,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[171,1412,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. Platypygus limatus, male specimen from Thailand: a — adult male (lateral view), b — adult male (dorsal view)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248559/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">
Fig. 
<number box="[450,478,788,813]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
b) yellow with large contiguous black pattern extending to base of scutellum, interhumeral marks, postpronotal lobes and postalar calli yellow; scutellum yellow; halter stem yellow, knob yellow ventrally, dark brown dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[601,686,860,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,249,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[184,1391,220,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[171,1412,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. Platypygus limatus, male specimen from Thailand: a — adult male (lateral view), b — adult male (dorsal view)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248559/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">
Fig. 
<number box="[656,686,860,884]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
a); vein Sc incomplete, not ending in costa; r-m crossvein before middle of cell dm; cell br slightly longer than cell bm; abdominal tergites (
<figureCitation box="[1004,1085,895,920]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,249,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[184,1391,220,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[171,1412,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. Platypygus limatus, male specimen from Thailand: a — adult male (lateral view), b — adult male (dorsal view)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248559/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="216">
Fig. 
<number box="[1057,1085,896,920]" pageId="17" pageNumber="216" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
a and b) black except posterior margins narrowly yellow, broader yellow laterally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
